    {
      "mode": "lesson",
      "words": [{ "w": "Note the following:" }]
    },
    {
      "words": [
        {
          "w": "1. هَذَا is pronounced هَازَا but it is written without the first alif."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "words": [
        {
          "w": "2. Arabic has no word corrosponding to the english \"is\", i.e. arabic has no copula. There is no word in Arabic corresponding to \"a\" in English as in \"this is a book\". The n-sound at the end of the Arabic noun(kitabu-n, baitu-n, masjidu-n) is the Arabic indefinite article corresponding to the English \"a\"/\"an\". This n-sound is called tanwin  "
        }
      ]
    },

    {
      "words": [
        {
          "w": "3. The particle أ placed at the begining of a statement turns it into a question, e.g."
        }
      ]
